e parser to the trace sink produces the expected trace artifact when given malformed input. This is testing the full integration of the parsing and tracing pipeline in actual execution.\n\nMinimum level: **System** — the \"real hook invocation path\" and the artifact output confirm this needs the complete end-to-end flow.\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing myself. The word \"real\" could just mean the full in-process pipeline wired together rather than subprocess invocation, which would make it Integration. But \"trace artifact\" suggests a tangible output like a file, which pushes toward System. I'm leaning Integration with a strong possibility it's System depending on how the trace sink works.\n\nFor the regression test behavior, this is really about verifying the parser can correctly distinguish between malformed JSON and valid markdown without misattributing errors. That's fundamentally a Unit or Integration test of the error handling logic with both input types. The minimum level is Integration.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering behavior 5 — the real hook invocation path that produces a trace artifact when given malformed input. If the trace sink writes to disk, that pushes it toward System testing since you need the actual process execution and file I/O to verify the artifact is created correctly.\n\nSo my final breakdown is: Unit for the parser logic, Integration for parser plus trace sink interaction, Unit for the error-policy handling, System for subprocess execution, System for the full hook invocation with artifact production, and Unit for the regression test that distinguishes input types at the parsing level. I should verify that behaviors 4 and 5 both genuinely require System-level testing before moving forward.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9760,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9760},"output_tokens":8,"serv